b'' b'two and a half years ago i purchased a set of cd roms from the' b'university of colorado lab for atmos. and space physics. they' b'were space sciences sampler and voyagers to the outer planets.' b'...' b'with pixel pusher we could never get past messages something like' b'this file has no pds label, please fill in the following info' b'(a bunch of slots with most zeros). yet, we could open the' b'image file in word and see the label file at the beginning.' b'' b'the compressed image format used for the voyager disks is not (yet)' b'supported by any macintosh display software that i know of. however,' b'there does exist a program that can convert the images to a format that' b'is recognized by recent versions of both pixel pusher and nih/image. it' b'is called "pds decompress" and is available via anonymous ftp from the' b'"pub" directory on "delcano.mit.edu" this is a binhex/' b'stuffit archive and contains the application itself, think-c source,' b'and a very brief description.' b'' b'the most recent version of nih/image may be down-loaded from' b'"starhawk.jpl.nasa.gov", where it is located in "image148.hqx" in the' b'"pub" directory. this archive also contains source code, but not the' b'documentation, which is located in the "image1455.hqx" archive in the' b'same directory.' b'' b'regards,' b'peter g. ford' b'manager, microwave subnode' b'nasa planetary data system' b'' 